Let (S \triangleleft P, \iota ^S, \sigma ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleleft Q, \iota ^T, \sigma ^T, \text {pr}^T) be monad containers. A distributive law of S \triangleleft P over T \triangleleft Q is given by the data:
\begin {align*} &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to T) \to T \\ &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to S \\ &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to P\ s \\ &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p)) \\ \end {align*}
where the following equalities hold:
\begin {align*} u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda \_ . \iota ^S)\\ u\ s\ (\lambda \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda \_. s)\\ v\ \{\iota ^S\}\ \{\lambda \_. t\} &= \langle \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\ v\ \{s\}\ \{\lambda \_. \iota ^T\} &= \langle \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\ \\ u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (u_1 \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\\ u_2\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}^S)\ q &= \sigma ^S\ (u_2\ s\ (u_1 \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\ q)\ (\lambda p . u_2\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (g\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (v_2\ q\ p))\\ \text {pr}^S_1\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\\ \text {pr}^S_2\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\ v_2\ q\ p &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\ \\ u_1\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ \langle f , g \rangle ) &= \sigma ^T\ (u_1\ s\ f)\ (\lambda q . u_1\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p)))\\ u_2\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ \langle f , g \rangle )\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q))\ (\lambda p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p))\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\ v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= v_1\ q\ p\\ v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= \text {pr}^T_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\ v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p &= \text {pr}^T_2\ (v_2\ q\ p) \end {align*}
We use the notation \langle f , g \rangle := \lambda x . (f\ x , g\ x), with some implicit use of currying and uncurrying where this shorthand is utilised.
u is defined as \langle u_1 , u_2 \rangle and v is defined as \langle v_1 , v_2 \rangle .

The data for these specialised distributive laws now becomes:

       \begin {align*}            &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  T) \to  T \\     &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to  T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to  S \\        \end {align*}   

  where the following equalities hold:

       \begin {align*}            u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda  \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^S)\\     u\ s\ (\lambda  \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda  \_. s)\\     \\      u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ  \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (u_1 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ  \text {pr}^S)\ q &= \sigma ^S\ (u_2\ s\ (u_1 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\ q)\ (\lambda  p . u_2\ (f\ p)\ (g\ p)\ q)\\       \\     u_1\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle ) &= \sigma ^T\ (u_1\ s\ f)\ (\lambda  q . u_1\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda  p . g\ p\ q))\\     u_2\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q))\ (\lambda  p . g\ p\ q)\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)        \end {align*}

We define the composite monad container (see composite container) (S \triangleleft  P \circ  T \triangleleft  Q, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) where

       \begin {align*}            \iota  &:= (\iota ^S , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^T)\\     \sigma \ (s , f)\ g &:= (\\       &\sigma ^S\ s\ (\lambda  p . u_1\ (f\ p)\ (g_1\ p)) ,\\       &\lambda  p . \sigma ^T\          (u_2\ (f\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (g_1\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p))\          (\lambda  q . g_2\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ q)\ (v_2\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ q))\\     &)\\     \text {pr}\ (p, q) &:= (\\     &(\text {pr}^S_1\ p , v_1\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)),\\      &(v_2\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q) , \text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\     &)        \end {align*}   

  where g_i := \pi _i \circ  g. The equations for this monad container hold given the equations for the two constituant monad containers and the distributive law. This is also a compatible composite of the two monad containers in question.

Let (A \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \sigma ^A, \text {pr}^A) and (B \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \sigma ^B, \text {pr}^B) be monad containers. By specialising the data and equations for a monad container distributive law to these, v_1 and v_2 become trivial (\text {pr}^A and \text {pr}^B are already trivial), and we are left with:

       \begin {align*}            u_1\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= b\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B) &= \iota ^B\\     u_1\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')) &= \sigma ^B\ (u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\\      u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \iota ^A\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B)\ * &= a\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \sigma ^A\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *)\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\ * &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *        \end {align*}   

  Bear in mind that, since all position sets are 1, we do not lose generality by assuming constant all of the functions in the equations above. By defining:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ a\ b := u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\\     \beta \ a\ b := u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *\\     a \otimes ^A a' := \sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a')\\     b \otimes ^B b' := \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')        \end {align*}   

  we can rewrite these equations as:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ \iota ^A\ b &= b\\     \alpha \ a\ \iota ^B &= \iota ^B\\     \alpha \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= \alpha \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)\\     \alpha \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= (\alpha \ a\ b) \otimes ^B (\alpha \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b')\\      \beta \ \iota ^A\ b &= \iota ^A\\     \beta \ a\ \iota ^B &= a\\     \beta \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= (\beta \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)) \otimes ^A (\beta \ a'\ b')\\     \beta \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= \beta \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b'        \end {align*}   

  These are exactly the equations exhibiting \alpha  and \beta  as a matching pair of monoid actions between (A, \otimes ^A, \iota ^A) and (B , \otimes ^B, \iota ^B). Therefore, monad container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let (1 \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . A, \downarrow ^A, o^A, \oplus ^A) and (1 \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . B, \downarrow ^B, o^B, \oplus ^B) be representable directed containers. By specialising the equations of a directed container distributive law to these, all equations involving u_2 disappear and we are left with:
       \begin {align*}       v_1\ b\ o^A &= o^A\\       v_1\ o^B\ a &= a\\       v_1\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_1\ b\ a \oplus ^A v_1\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_1\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_1\ b\ (v_1\ b'\ a)\\       v_2\ b\ o^A &= b\\       v_2\ o^B\ a &= o^B\\       v_2\ b\ (a \oplus ^A a') &= v_2\ (v_2\ b\ a)\ a'\\       v_2\ (b \oplus ^B b')\ a &= v_2\ b\ (v_1\ b' a) \oplus ^B v_2\ b'\ a     \end {align*}   
  which exhibit v_1 and v_2 as a matching pair of monoid maps between the monoids (A , o^A, \oplus ^A) and (B, o^B, \oplus ^B). Hence, directed container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

Let (A \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^A, \sigma ^A, \text {pr}^A) and (B \triangleleft  \lambda  \_ . 1, \iota ^B, \sigma ^B, \text {pr}^B) be monad containers. By specialising the data and equations for a monad container distributive law to these, v_1 and v_2 become trivial (\text {pr}^A and \text {pr}^B are already trivial), and we are left with:

       \begin {align*}            u_1\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= b\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B) &= \iota ^B\\     u_1\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b) &= u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\\     u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')) &= \sigma ^B\ (u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\\      u_2\ \iota ^A\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \iota ^A\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota ^B)\ * &= a\\     u_2\ (\sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a'))\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ * &= \sigma ^A\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . u_1\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b))\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . u_2\ a'\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *)\\     u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b'))\ * &= u_2\ (u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *)\ (\lambda  \_ . b')\ *        \end {align*}   

  Bear in mind that, since all position sets are 1, we do not lose generality by assuming constant all of the functions in the equations above. By defining:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ a\ b := u_1\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\\     \beta \ a\ b := u_2\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . b)\ *\\     a \otimes ^A a' := \sigma ^A\ a\ (\lambda  \_ . a')\\     b \otimes ^B b' := \sigma ^B\ b\ (\lambda  \_ . b')        \end {align*}   

  we can rewrite these equations as:

       \begin {align*}            \alpha \ \iota ^A\ b &= b\\     \alpha \ a\ \iota ^B &= \iota ^B\\     \alpha \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= \alpha \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)\\     \alpha \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= (\alpha \ a\ b) \otimes ^B (\alpha \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b')\\      \beta \ \iota ^A\ b &= \iota ^A\\     \beta \ a\ \iota ^B &= a\\     \beta \ (a \otimes ^A a')\ b &= (\beta \ a\ (\alpha \ a'\ b)) \otimes ^A (\beta \ a'\ b')\\     \beta \ a\ (b \otimes ^B b') &= \beta \ (\beta \ a\ b)\ b'        \end {align*}   

  These are exactly the equations exhibiting \alpha  and \beta  as a matching pair of monoid actions between (A, \otimes ^A, \iota ^A) and (B , \otimes ^B, \iota ^B). Therefore, monad container distributive laws of this type are in bijection with matching pairs of actions for the relevant monoids.

We define the composite monad container (see composite container) (S \triangleleft  P \circ  T \triangleleft  Q, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) where

       \begin {align*}            \iota  &:= (\iota ^S , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^T)\\     \sigma \ (s , f)\ g &:= (\\       &\sigma ^S\ s\ (\lambda  p . u_1\ (f\ p)\ (g_1\ p)) ,\\       &\lambda  p . \sigma ^T\          (u_2\ (f\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (g_1\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p))\          (\lambda  q . g_2\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ q)\ (v_2\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ q))\\     &)\\     \text {pr}\ (p, q) &:= (\\     &(\text {pr}^S_1\ p , v_1\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)),\\      &(v_2\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q) , \text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\     &)        \end {align*}   

  where g_i := \pi _i \circ  g. The equations for this monad container hold given the equations for the two constituant monad containers and the distributive law. This is also a compatible composite of the two monad containers in question.

Let S \triangleleft  P be a container. A monad container (or mnd-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleleft  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \iota  &: S\\       \sigma  &: \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  S) \to  S\\       \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  S\}} P\ (\sigma \ s\ f) \to  \sum _{p : P\ s} P\ (f\ p)     \end {align*}   
  For which the following laws hold:
       \begin {align*}       \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota  ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ \iota \ (\lambda  \_ . a ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ (\sigma \ a\ f)\ (\lambda  p . g\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)) &= \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  p . \sigma \ (f\ p)\ (g\ p))\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)     \end {align*}   
  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \sigma  above them.
